<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="80" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1214,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1359,1383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">Etymology</emphasis>
: The species epithet, an adjective, refers to the similarity of this species to polydesmidan millipedes of the family 
<taxonomicName box="[433,608,1394,1418]" class="Diplopoda" family="Pyrgodesmidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polydesmida" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pyrgodesmidae</taxonomicName>
, with similar depressed paranota, rough cuticle covered in adhering soil, and paramedian elevations of the metazonites.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="85" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1214,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,1466,1491]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">Description:</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[354,524,1467,1491]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
Male 
<typeStatus box="[420,520,1467,1491]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</emphasis>
Length, 8.5 mm, width 2.0–2.2 mm, including paranota. Head typical, smooth, yellowish tan mottled purplish gray to brown. Ocelli 
<number box="[752,768,1502,1526]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="6.0">6</number>
, in rows of 
<number box="[900,943,1502,1526]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="3.2">3, 2</number>
, 
<number box="[955,970,1502,1526]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="1.0">1</number>
. Collum partially covering head (
<figureCitation box="[1353,1419,1502,1526]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1522,1545]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,197,1493]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,197,1494]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Pyrgeuma pyrgodesmoides, n. sp., male, dorsal views. Fig. 1. Anterior end. Fig. 2. Posterior end. Fig. 3. Rings 8 – 10." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/213350/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
Fig. 
<number box="[1406,1419,1502,1526]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
), more than twice as wide as head, with horizontal paranota laterally acute-rounded, markedly elevated posterior ridge, metazonital cuticle with vestiture of minute, curved, spatulate microtrichia averaging about 
<number box="[1250,1278,1574,1598]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="20.0">20</number>
µm in length; marginal microtrichia small, in rows, longer microtrichia along horizontal midline of paranota. On subsequent trunk rings, posterior ridge progressively depressed in midline, forming paramedian elevations becoming more prominent posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[426,542,1682,1706]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1522,1545]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,197,1493]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,197,1494]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Pyrgeuma pyrgodesmoides, n. sp., male, dorsal views. Fig. 1. Anterior end. Fig. 2. Posterior end. Fig. 3. Rings 8 – 10." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/213350/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
Figs. 
<number box="[498,542,1682,1706]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Paranota narrow, not as wide as metazonites, slightly depressed, with anterobasal notch (
<figureCitation box="[364,434,1718,1742]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1522,1545]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,197,1493]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,197,1494]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Pyrgeuma pyrgodesmoides, n. sp., male, dorsal views. Fig. 1. Anterior end. Fig. 2. Posterior end. Fig. 3. Rings 8 – 10." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/213350/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
Fig. 
<number box="[418,434,1718,1742]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Metazonital setae not detectable at magnifications up to 
<number box="[1102,1146,1718,1742]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="210.0">210</number>
X, on midbody rings only slightly longer than microtrichia, blunt, with 
<number box="[660,703,1754,1778]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="6.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="5.0">5–7</number>
prominent ridges (Figs. 
<number box="[982,1027,1754,1778]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="4.5">4, 5</number>
, 
<number box="[1040,1071,1754,1778]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="12.0">12</number>
). Epiproct (Figs. 
<number box="[1277,1320,1754,1778]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="4.5">4, 5</number>
) rounded, median pair of setae three times as long as usual (ca. 
<number box="[749,777,1790,1814]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="60.0">60</number>
µm long), spinnerets prominent, spinneret setae long, anal valves with few long setae. Collum, body rings, epiproct appear dark brown, due to adhering soil. Venter, legs yellowish white.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1214,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
Gonopods (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[335,384,1899,1922]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">agp,</emphasis>
<figureCitation box="[395,478,1898,1922]" captionStart="FIGURES 8, 9" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,176,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,147,1875]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8, 9. Pyrgeuma pyrgodesmoides, n. sp., male. Fig. 8. Gonopods and ninth legs, anterior view. Agp, gonopods; c 9, coxites of ninth legpair; pf 9, prefemora of ninth legpair. Fig. 9. Tenth legpair, anterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/213351/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
Figs. 
<number box="[462,478,1898,1922]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="8.1">8</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[494,568,1898,1922]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1628,1651]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1607]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1607]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 12. Pyrgeuma pyrgodesmoides, n. sp., male. Fig. 10. Coxites of left ninth legpair (c 9) and gonopods (agp), posterior view. Fig. 11. Tip of left gonopod, anterior view. Fig. 12. Lateralmost right metazonital seta of ring 9." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/213352/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
10, 
<number box="[541,568,1898,1922]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
) fused to coxosternite, to each other at base, complex; erect, not passing laterally, posteriorly to ninth leg coxites (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[628,655,1934,1959]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
c 
<number box="[640,655,1934,1959]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="9.0">9</number>
</emphasis>
, 
<figureCitation box="[672,752,1934,1958]" captionStart="FIGURES 8, 9" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,176,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,147,1875]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8, 9. Pyrgeuma pyrgodesmoides, n. sp., male. Fig. 8. Gonopods and ninth legs, anterior view. Agp, gonopods; c 9, coxites of ninth legpair; pf 9, prefemora of ninth legpair. Fig. 9. Tenth legpair, anterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/213351/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
Figs. 
<number box="[736,752,1934,1958]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="8.1">8</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[767,798,1934,1958]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1628,1651]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1607]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1607]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 12. Pyrgeuma pyrgodesmoides, n. sp., male. Fig. 10. Coxites of left ninth legpair (c 9) and gonopods (agp), posterior view. Fig. 11. Tip of left gonopod, anterior view. Fig. 12. Lateralmost right metazonital seta of ring 9." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/213352/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">10</figureCitation>
). Ninth leg telopodites one-articled, swollen; ninth leg coxites with long, acute mesal branch, shorter lateral branch tipped with three or four horizontally extending thorns (
<figureCitation box="[159,243,2006,2030]" captionStart="FIGURES 10 – 12" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1628,1651]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1607]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,193,1607]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 10 – 12. Pyrgeuma pyrgodesmoides, n. sp., male. Fig. 10. Coxites of left ninth legpair (c 9) and gonopods (agp), posterior view. Fig. 11. Tip of left gonopod, anterior view. Fig. 12. Lateralmost right metazonital seta of ring 9." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/213352/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
Fig. 
<number box="[212,243,2006,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
). Tenth legs (
<figureCitation box="[401,468,2006,2030]" captionStart="FIGURES 8, 9" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,176,1875]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,147,1875]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8, 9. Pyrgeuma pyrgodesmoides, n. sp., male. Fig. 8. Gonopods and ninth legs, anterior view. Agp, gonopods; c 9, coxites of ninth legpair; pf 9, prefemora of ninth legpair. Fig. 9. Tenth legpair, anterior view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/213351/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="80">
Fig. 
<number box="[453,468,2006,2030]" pageId="1" pageNumber="80" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
) with coxae slightly enlarged, bearing glands, telopodite reduced to two short articles.
</paragraph>
<caption httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/213350/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" targetBox="[151,1435,197,1493]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1522,1576]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,316,1522,1545]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">FIGURES 1–3.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[331,611,1523,1545]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
<taxonomicName box="[331,607,1523,1545]" class="Diplopoda" family="Heterochordeumatidae" genus="Pyrgeuma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pyrgodesmoides" status="n. sp.">Pyrgeuma pyrgodesmoides</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[619,675,1524,1545]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, male, dorsal views. Fig. 1. Anterior end. Fig. 2. Posterior end. Fig. 3. Rings 8–10.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1620,1991]" box="[199,1263,1620,1644]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
Female with 
<number box="[345,373,1620,1644]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="32.0">32</number>
rings; 9.2 mm long, 2.0–2.2 mm wide; similar to male in nonsexual characters.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1620,1991]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,275,1655,1679]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">Notes:</emphasis>
The microtrichia of the dorsal surface of the metazonites do not appear to be set in sockets, so instead of setae they are direct outgrowths of the cuticle. They vary in size and distribution; the smallest microtrichia are densely arranged in rows on the anterior and posterior edges of the paranota. Larger microtrichia are found sparsely scattered on the anterior part of the metazonite, and microtrichia of similar size are densely arranged on the elevated parts and along the horizontal midline of each paranotum (
<figureCitation box="[946,1025,1794,1818]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 3" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1522,1545]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,197,1493]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,197,1494]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 3. Pyrgeuma pyrgodesmoides, n. sp., male, dorsal views. Fig. 1. Anterior end. Fig. 2. Posterior end. Fig. 3. Rings 8 – 10." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/213350/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="81">
Figs. 
<number box="[1009,1025,1794,1818]" pageId="2" pageNumber="81" value="3.6">3</number>
</figureCitation>
, 6). The largest and most prominent microtrichia are on the paramedian knobs. While the microtrichia, with their curved, spatulate shapes, appear welladapted for catching and holding soil particles, the particles appear to be held on mostly by a gummy secretion and could only be partially cleaned off using ultrasonics. The mixture of secretion, small soil particles and humic materials appears ropy. Scattered among the microtrichia are very small spherical objects that may represent this secretion, but no glandular pores could be detected even at high magnification under the SEM.
</paragraph>
